    <table>
      <caption>Guard Passing</caption>

      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th scope="col" style="width: 120px"></th>
          <th scope="col">Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <th scope="row">General</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>
                In general, you want to clear grips, close the distance, and
                stay close to pass guard. This is generally easier to do in a
                gi. No-gi tends to use a tighter style of guard passing (body
                locks, underhooks) to maintain connection.
              </li>
              <li>
                Guard pass categories: around the legs, through the legs, under
                the legs
              </li>
              <li>
                Think of passing techniques as methods of transition between
                staging positions (positions of advantage that provide
                stability)—when your path seems blocked, you may see openings
                toward other staging positions
              </li>
            </ul>

            Guard passing heuristics:
            <ul>
              <li>Make your opponent face away from you</li>
              <li>Bring one side of your opponent’s hips to the mat</li>
              <li>
                Maneuver around your opponent’s frames (attack them at angles
                rather than straight on)
              </li>
              <li>
                Lift your weight slightly off a frame to make it easier to clear
              </li>
              <li>Maintain knee-elbow connection to protect against attacks</li>
              <li>Separate your opponent’s knees from their chest</li>
              <li>
                Stay on top (don’t just stay down if your opponent is in the
                process of sweeping you)
              </li>
              <li>
                Work through the layers of the guard (feet → knees → hips →
                arms)
              </li>
              <li>
                Avoid leg entanglements (keep your feet out of range, strip
                grips on your leg, tripod and wedge against your opponent’s body
                with your head, drop your leg to the ground, etc.)
              </li>
              <li>
                “2 steps forward, 1 step back”: Transition to a different
                staging position if you’re about to lose your position
              </li>
              <li>
                Stay on the balls of your feet so you can move faster and drive
                into your opponent
              </li>
              <li>Keep your opponent’s feet off your torso</li>
              <li>
                Get the far-side underhook (it keeps you close to your opponent,
                makes it more difficult for them to frame, and keeps you from
                being bumped forward), but don’t reach for it if you haven’t
                passed or dealt with at least one of your opponent’s legs (that
                will put you into closed guard)
              </li>
              <li>
                Don’t let your opponent underhook you (under the arm, around the
                waist, or under the leg)--block their arm and exert your own
                underhook
              </li>
              <li>Get the crossface</li>
              <li>
                Control your opponent’s hips (e.g., underhook their waist to
                prevent them from hip escaping)
              </li>
              <li>
                Fatigue your opponent (some positions are inherently tiring for
                the bottom person—e.g., getting stacked)
              </li>
              <li>
                Learn to pass while standing up (you have better mobility than
                when you’re kneeling)
              </li>
              <li>
                Control your opponent’s bottom leg (makes it hard for them to
                make space or stand up—they need to retract their bottom leg to
                stand up)
              </li>
              <li>
                Control your opponent’s bottom arm (hard to stand up without
                posting on your bottom arm)
              </li>
              <li>
                Win the inside position (push the insides of your opponent’s
                legs, as the adductors tend to be relatively weak). Clear leg
                frames from the inside before moving to the outside of your
                opponent’s legs.
              </li>
              <li>
                Use windshield wipers to pass over limbs without making large
                movements
              </li>
              <li>Use your head to wedge and post</li>
              <li>
                Keep your legs just within reach (not close enough for your
                opponent to get good grips but not too far that you have poor
                mobility and leave your arms unsupported by the rest of your
                body)—if your opponent reaches for a grip, they’ll open up for
                you to get closer and get more control
              </li>
              <li>
                Use posts to maintain base and active posts to redirect your
                pressure as needed
              </li>
              <li>
                In general, you want your elbows/knees tight and arms/feet out
                wide when passing (tight for control, wide for posting)
              </li>
              <li>
                Take your opponent out of their element (e.g., make them switch
                from seated guard to recumbent guard and vice versa, pass
                outside their legs if they try to put their legs inside yours)
              </li>
              <li>
                Catch your opponent between supine and seated (e.g., spin your
                opponent around while they only have one point of contact with
                the floor, close the distance as your opponent is sitting up)
              </li>
            </ul>

            Guard passing postures:
            <ul>
              <li>
                Combat base - one leg leading + elbow-knee connection, other leg
                back for mobility (can be standing or kneeling)
              </li>
              <li>
                Full squat - useful when your opponent has good upper body
                control of you while in gi (squatting closes the space between
                your armpits and legs)
              </li>
              <li>
                Kneeling - prevents leg entanglements, can also be used in half
                guard and closed guard; poor mobility and bad for offense
              </li>
              <li>
                Tripod - useful for keeping pressure on your opponent’s torso
                while walking your feet up above their knees (e.g., when your
                opponent has a knee shield); can also block your opponent’s knee
                from their chest and collapse frames
              </li>
              <li>
                Tall posture - useful for putting pressure on an opponent’s
                collar grip
              </li>
              <li>
                Gorilla posture - useful for moving around the legs when
                passing; hips over feet (for mobility), shoulders forward of or
                above hands (so you can push weight down)
              </li>
              <li>
                Knee through (cross-knee or near-side) - one knee stapling the
                opponent’s bottom leg, the other leg stepped up, hovering your
                weight over your opponent
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>
